Chapter 4 of Data Camp - Intro to Time Series Analsys

Autoregressive model (AR)

See supplemental slides for details

To create an AR model use the arima.sim() function and specify the slope with the mode = list(ar=mu).

Simplest case is the Model - 1.

The AR recursion is

Today = Constant + Slope * Yesterday + Noise

Mean centerd version:

(Today - Mean) = Slope * (Yesterda - Mean) + Noise

Or

\(Y_t - \mu = \phi(Y_{t-1} - \mu) + \epsilon_t\) where \(\epsilon_t\) is mean zero WN.

3 Parms:

  • Mean \(\mu\)
  • Slope \(\phi\)
  • The WN variace \(\sigma_{\epsilon}^2\)

If \(\phi = 0\) then \(Y_t = \mu + \epsilon_t\) and \(Y_t\) is White Noise \((\mu, \sigma_{\epsilon}^2)\).

If \(\phi \ne 0\) then \(Y_t\) depends on both \(\epsilon_t\) and \(Y_{t-1}\) and the process \({Y_t}\) is autocorrelated.

  • Large values of \(\phi\) lead to greater correlation
  • Negative values of \(\phi\) lead to oscillatory ts.

Random Walk

If \(\mu = 0\) and slope \(\phi = 1\) then \(Y_t = Y_{t-1} + \epsilon_t\) which is Random Walk.

x <- arima.sim(model=list(ar=0.5), n=100)

# Simulate an AR model with 0.9 slope
y <- arima.sim(model=list(ar=0.9), n=100)

# Simulate an AR model with -0.75 slope
z <- arima.sim(model=list(ar=(-0.75)), n=100)

# Plot your simulated data
plot.ts(cbind(x, y, z))

ACF

par(mfrow=c(3,1))
acf(x)
acf(y)
acf(z)

Persistence / AntiPersistence

  • Persistence is defined by high correlation between an observation and its lag.
  • Antipersistence is defined by a large amount of variation between an observation and its lag.
x <- arima.sim(model = list(ar=0.9), n = 200)
ts.plot(x)

acf(x)

# Simulate and plot AR model with slope 0.98
y <- arima.sim(model=list(ar=0.98), n=200)
ts.plot(y)

acf(y)

# Simulate and plot RW model
z <- arima.sim(model=list(order=c(0,1,0)), n=200)
ts.plot(z)

acf(z)

AR Model Estimating and Forecasting

an AR model is ARIMA(1, 0, 0)

Lets fit an arima model to AirPassengers and plot it as well as teh fited values.

The fitted values are simply the original data less the residuals, which can be extracted with the residuals() function.

data("AirPassengers")

AR <- arima(AirPassengers, order=c(1, 0, 0))
print(AR)
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = AirPassengers, order = c(1, 0, 0))
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1  intercept
##       0.9669   275.5774
## s.e.  0.0207    68.2627
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 1035:  log likelihood = -705.52,  aic = 1417.04
ts.plot(AirPassengers)
AR_fitted <- AirPassengers - residuals(AR)
points(AR_fitted, type = "l", col = 2, lty = 2)

Simple forecasts

The predict() function is used to predict the future!

data("Nile")

AR_fit <-arima(Nile, order  = c(1, 0, 0))
print(AR_fit)
## 
## Call:
## arima(x = Nile, order = c(1, 0, 0))
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1  intercept
##       0.5063   919.5685
## s.e.  0.0867    29.1410
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 21125:  log likelihood = -639.95,  aic = 1285.9
# Use predict() to make a 1-step forecast
predict_AR <- predict(AR_fit)

# Obtain the 1-step forecast using $pred[1]
predict_AR$pred[1]
## [1] 828.6576
# Use predict to make 1-step through 10-step forecasts
predict(AR_fit, n.ahead = 10)
## $pred
## Time Series:
## Start = 1971 
## End = 1980 
## Frequency = 1 
##  [1] 828.6576 873.5426 896.2668 907.7715 913.5960 916.5448 918.0377
##  [8] 918.7935 919.1762 919.3699
## 
## $se
## Time Series:
## Start = 1971 
## End = 1980 
## Frequency = 1 
##  [1] 145.3439 162.9092 167.1145 168.1754 168.4463 168.5156 168.5334
##  [8] 168.5380 168.5391 168.5394
# Run to plot the Nile series plus the forecast and 95% prediction intervals
ts.plot(Nile, xlim = c(1871, 1980))
AR_forecast <- predict(AR_fit, n.ahead = 10)$pred
AR_forecast_se <- predict(AR_fit, n.ahead = 10)$se
points(AR_forecast, type = "l", col = 2)
points(AR_forecast - 2*AR_forecast_se, type = "l", col = 2, lty = 2)
points(AR_forecast + 2*AR_forecast_se, type = "l", col = 2, lty = 2)
